, Wales","Wychnor, Staffordshire, Wales":"Wychnor, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Wichnal, Tatenhill, Staffordshire, England":"Tatenhill, Staffordshire, England","Leicestershire":"Leicestershire, England","Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"1351–after 1380":"1351–after 1380","1351–1380":"1351–1380","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1371–1439":"1371–1439","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1326–1396":"1326–1396","about 1370":"about 1370","Abt. 1380":"about 1380","about 1371":"about 1371","after 1380":"after 1380","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1326":"1326","1325":"1325","1368":"1368","27 May 1380":"27 May 1380","1439":"1439","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wychnor, Staffordshire, Wales":"Wychnor, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Wichnal, Tatenhill, Staffordshire, England":"Tatenhill, Staffordshire, England","Leicestershire":"Leicestershire, England","Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stackpole","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: habitational name from Stackpole (Pembrokeshire), apparently named with Old Norse <i>stakkr</i> ‘stack’ + <i>pollr</i> ‘pool’, referring to a stack of rocks on the coast at the entrance to Broadhaven. The name was taken to Ireland and adapted by settlers of Norman descent, where it is recorded in Dublin as early as 1200. The name has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stacapúl</b>; the family was also known in Irish as <b>Galldubh</b> ‘dark stranger’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stackpoole","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Welsh: variant of   Stackpole  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel de Stackpole was born in 1351, in Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales as the daughter of Richard de Stackpole III. She married Rhys Griffith II in 1368, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died after 1380, in Wychnor, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1351–after 1380":"1351–pärast 1380","1351–1380":"1351–1380","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1371–1439":"1371–1439","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1326–1396":"1326–1396","about 1370":"umbes 1370","Abt. 1380":"umbes 1380","about 1371":"umbes 1371","after 1380":"pärast 1380","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1326":"1326","1325":"1325","1368":"1368","27 May 1380":"27. mai 1380","1439":"1439","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wychnor, Staffordshire, Wales":"Wychnor, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Wichnal, Tatenhill, Staffordshire, England":"Tatenhill, Staffordshire, England","Leicestershire":"Leicestershire, England","Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1351–after 1380":"1351–1380 jälkeen","1351–1380":"1351–1380","1325–1380":"1325–1380","137